==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|incarceratus}}, past participle of {{term|incarcerare||to imprison|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|in||in|lang=la}} + {{term|carcer||a prison|lang=la}}, meaning "put behind lines (bars)" – Latin root is of a lattice or grid. Related to {{term|cancel||cross out with lines|lang=en}} and {{term|chancel||area behind a lattice|lang=en}}.

See also {{term|carcerate|lang=en}} and {{term|cancer|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ɪnˈkɑː.sə.ɹeɪt/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|incarcerat|ing}}

# To [[lock away]]; to [[imprison]], especially for breaking the law.
# To [[confine]].

====Usage notes====
As a Latinate term, somewhat formal, compared to {{term|imprison|lang=en}}.

